<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;loral&#64;loralciriclight&#46;com">Loral</a> at September 29, 2004 01:52 PM</strong></p>
<p>The majority of players under 50 statistic includes active players and excludes bazaar mules.  The majority of active characters are under level 50.  I don't know exactly what defines "active" but probably logging on once a week counts.</p>

<p>This does not mean, however, that they play the most amount of time.  I bet the most amount of time online goes to 65+ characters.  However, time online or not, we all pay the same price.</p>

<p>I heard another unattributable statistic that 85% of EQ players are not level 65 raiders.  Again, I have few details on the statistic.</p>

<p>Statistics alone don't tell us what Everquest needs.  What it does tell me, however, is that the bulk of players don't need high-end raid content.  They need features that help them play the game.  They need features that help EQ fit into their busy lives.  They need features that help players under 50 find a group, find a place to hunt, and find an easy way out when they have to go.</p>

<p>The features I agree with the most are the features that affect players of all levels such as the task system, the chat channels, the LFG tool, the tribute changes, the augment swapping changes, the LDON item returns, progressive equipment systems like the LDON point system, and instanced content with scaling level ranges.</p>

<p>The features I do not agree with include flagging solutions that only support high-end raiding guilds, raid flags that lead to single-group hunting zones (like Fire), the instancing of the Plane of Time (high development time for a two-year old zone), focus solutions that only support high-end raiding equipment, and large power gaps in equipment between raiders and single-group hunters.</p>

<p>For Everquest to continue to grow they need to get more players who only have a few hours a week to play.  Mini-games, improved task systems, enhanced LDON-style dungeons, better grouping tools, and an easier interface to learn all help bring new players in.</p>

<p>Everquest cannot survive by only supporting the upper 15% of the player population.  They need to bring new players in.</p>

<p>SOE does a good job of implementing solutions that affect the majority of players and I expect to see more in the future.  They know their business far better than I.</p>
