<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://claws.guildportal.com" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=280">Talaen</a> at September 29, 2004 03:18 PM</strong></p>
<p>Here is my take on Omens of War:</p>

<p>From a graphics and sound perspective, I believe the expansion was very well done.  I am very happy with the look, feel, and overall atmosphere of the expansion.  That said, I have some guildmates who are having serious video problems since Omens went live - to the point where they can't play.  Obviously this is very frustrating for them and I hope that SOEs tech support team can find and fix the issues quickly.</p>

<p>On content:  Most of the zones are set up very well for what would seem to be their intended level ranges.  I especially like how some zones, like the causeway, get tougher the further into them you go.  This allows folks to move deeper in for more challenge and more rewards.</p>

<p>The new epic quests which have been added are, at least from what I have seen and read, very epic.  They bring back the feel of the original in that this is something that transcends the simple act of accumulating gear and experience.</p>

<p>However, I have some problems with the content in Omens. First, the instanced expeditions are too thin.  Most players are using them simply as a way to farm experience and a few loot drops.  There needs to be more to them - either some purpose to you being in that area, or more named mobs and loot.  Something to keep folks from clearing them up to one particular room and then sitting there working on spell runes or whatever particular piece of gear they were after.  I don't necessarily think a timer is a good idea - these zones are huge and a timer would unfairly limit less powerful groups.  However, I do think that there should be much more scripting involved.</p>

<p>Second, it is extremely difficult for players to get involved in the storyline of Omens.  The factions only halfway make sense.  I think that people -should- have to pay attention to factions, but they should also be able to actually get involved in the storyline from day 1, rather than having to kill tons of things to raise a faction that may or may not make a difference in the end.  As most players simply ignore faction until someone has posted a powerful quest item on the web, this really only penalizes people who want to explore for the sake of learning.</p>

<p>Finally, while i do very much like the new epic quests, their release has reminded me of what I hate most about EQ - and that is the tendency of most players to focus solely on the levels and the loot and not on the story or the world itself.  People don't go to zones to see somewhere new, they go because it's "better experience" or has a piece of loot they want.  They will happily destroy their faction in their hometown to get an item with better stats from an opposing faction's quest.  To give you an example, the other day some friends and I were in Kaesora getting Xalgoz fangs for the Charasis Key quest.  A group of 66+ players zoned in, and quite politely asked us which epic we were working on that we needed to get into Charasis.  When we told them we just wanted to go there to see the place and find its secrets, they tried (again very politely) to tell us that we were wasting our time.  This to me exemplifies what is very wrong with EQ - the loot mentality that it instills in its players is the same one that eventually burns most players out on the game.</p>

<p>On itemization - This could have been done better.  There are some nice upgrades in Omens, to be sure.  However, there seem to be two classes of gear there - either extremely nice to the point that people fight over it, or okay but not really much better than what people already had.  This lack of a middle ground really hurts - it means that certain mobs and zones get camped to death while others go untouched.</p>

<p>Likewise, the spell runes are better than GoD, but still frustrating to many people.  Along with many of the nice-but-not-awesome items, I think these should probably be changed to rare drops from any mob in their zones, rather than rare drops from named mobs only.</p>

<p>The biggest problem I see with itemization is that the class requirements on many items don't seem to make sense.  I've been seeing a lot of gear that's listed for all hybrid classes, for example.  Since I'm a hybrid, that's great, but if I as a paladin can wear a piece of armor, shouldn't a warrior be able to wear it?  Or a cleric?  Sometimes I really wonder if the people who do itemization for new zones and expansions at SOE really take into account anything that's gone before them in the game.</p>

<p>On difficulty:  I have mixed feelings on this.  I am happy with the challenge level of many encounters - especially some of the encounters I have had deeper in the Omens zones where you really had to pay attention to how the mobs were fighting and come up with a good set of tactics to defeat it.  I also like how you have to pay attention to the environment in some places.  Ideally, I think the challenge of any area should be at least partially (30%) determined by the environment - narrow walkways, water, etc.</p>

<p>However, you could cut the hp of most Omens mobs by 1/3 or even 1/2 and the fights would still be difficult.  As it stands, most encounters basically degenerate into hitting auto-attack and waiting 5 minutes.  While I understand the need for making the mobs tough enough to keep players from clearing out the zone, this is a little extreme.  It's especially glaring when you have a minimal group or one that's low on damage-dealing classes, where individual fights can take nearly ten minutes to complete.  This ultimately just becomes boring.  Longer fights do not generally make for harder fights.</p>

<p>Getting to places isn't very hard once you learn the way there, but it's dangerous enough to keep you on your toes.  I do think that every expansion since at least Legacy of Ykesha has been forcing players to become more and more dependant on invisibility potions, and that's a bad thing.</p>

<p>Overall I think Omens is a good expansion, worth the money, and is much more solid and available than its predecessor, but I also think that it could use a good bit of tweaking and rebalancing.  Then again, the whole game could use that in my view.  There have been so many mistakes made, and so many bandaids applied over the past few years, that it seems impossible that one expansion cold really fix much of anything.</p>
