<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;wolfshead&#64;comcast&#46;net">Wolfshead</a> at October  2, 2004 10:04 AM</strong></p>
<p>I think many of the zones were rushed. SOE just can't seem to figure out a way to make mob populations realistic. For example there are only 2 zones that have any animal life at all in Omens: Dranik's Scar and Wall of Slaughter. It is very unrealistic to have outdoor zones with zero animal life. Some zones have a mob population density that is excessive. Dranik's Scar looks like rush hour in Manhattan. Ruined City of Dranik is yet another terrible zone with mobs occupying every square inch of real estate like so many bowling pins. I long for the day that zones were handcrafed and mobs were placed with some semblance of meaning--unlike Omens.</p>

<p>Another problem is there are almost no undead nor summoned mobs to speak of despite the fact that many classes get new anti-summoned and anti-undead spells. From a believability point of view these spells are supposed to be "magic" from Kuaa. Why then would those that practice magic in Kuaa create anti-summoned spells when there are zero summoned mob in their lands? Also how convenient that the currency of Kuaa is plat and gold despite being in another universe. Good job making this unreleastic SOE.</p>

<p>Another problem is where are the DC pets in this expansion? Only the newbie zone has them and for all intents and purposes makes them useless for high level players. At least in PoP the devs ensured that most zones had mobs that could be Dire Charmed. Sadly the current Dev Team *hates* charm in every way shape or form. Even Advanced Dire Charm which is listed in the Omens PDF manual that is in your EverQuest directory was removed from the expansion.</p>

<p>Lastly, where is this "war" that is supposed to be ravaging Omens? Where are the massive battles going on? Why aren't the subjegated Dragorn fighting back against the Muramite Legion? Where is the innovation of Omens? Once you get past the Peter Jackson LOTR inspired scenery and eye candy, it's all the same old stuff but with a few new NPC models. The online gaming genre has not been advanced on iota with Omens. It's the same old song and dance--just levels and more loot.</p>

<p>I'd say that at least 70% of my guild or more is poised and ready to migrate to World of Warcraft once it's released at the end of this year. SOE has shown us that all they care about is the money and that releasing a quality, well tuned, innovative expansion is beyond them.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;khuas&#64;shaw&#46;ca_no_spam">Khuas</a> at October  2, 2004 02:27 PM</strong></p>
<p>Are there any "events" in OoW like there were in Luclin and Velious? Stuff like those crazy owlbears fighting the wolves, and the giants warring with the dragons and dwarves?</p>

<p>It is that sorta thing that I miss. I want to somehow feel as though I've participated in something, even if just for a little while. I have zero motivation to follow the storyline in OoW. Heck, I don't even know what the storyline is supposed to be in OoW. You certainly can't derive that from the game content itself - you have to get it from the lore section on the website. Just that alone makes me think this was just a "throw 'em some more zones and levels until we can get EQ2 out" thing. Yeah, no black helicopters hovering over my house. =)</p>

<p>I have no comments for the task system, save to say I don't think they were really designed for those level 50+. I think they were added on quite late in the cycle and rushed.</p>

<p>I guess I am not being particularly objective. I have issues with SOE churning out thoughtless expansions that more/less trivialize previous content, especially when the previous content had issues that still haven't been addressed. </p>
